The result you get, is precisely telling you what is happening. Neither of your methods is invoking the constructor.

All of your methods have the form

    @Test
    @MarkerN
    public void fX() {
        Z.g();
    }
so they contain an invocation of the `static` method `g()` of class `Z`. But no instantiation of `Z`.

Instead, your classes `A` and `B` are subclasses of `Z`. Since you didn’t declare explicit constructors for them, the compiler generates default constructors for them, like

    public class A extends Z {

        public A() {
            super(); // here, the constructor of Z gets called
        }


    // the other methods …

    }

and so, the reflective lookup will tell you that the invocation of `Z`’s constructor happens inside a method named `&lt;init&gt;`, which is `A`’s constructor, resp. `B`’s constructor for `B`.

It would be different if the methods did `new Z().g()`, but that would make the questionable design of relying on a constructor being executed before a `static` method invocation even worse.

This issue should be solved on the framework side, which is doing both, instantiating `A` and `B` and invoking the methods `f1()` to `f4()` on them. E.g. with JUnit&#160;5, the solution would look like:

    
    package test;
    
    import java.lang.annotation.*;
    import java.lang.reflect.AnnotatedElement;
    import org.junit.jupiter.api.*;
    
    public class A {
        @BeforeEach
        public void prepare(TestInfo ti) {
            Z.loadConfiguration(ti.getTestMethod().get());
        }
        @Test
        @Marker1
        public void f1() {
            Z.g();
        }
        @Test
        @Marker2
        public void f2() {
            Z.g();
        }
    }
    
    class Z {
        public static void loadConfiguration(AnnotatedElement e) {
            if(e.isAnnotationPresent(Marker1.class)) {
                System.out.println(&quot;Marker1&quot;);
            }
            else if(e.isAnnotationPresent(Marker2.class)) {
                System.out.println(&quot;Marker2&quot;);
            } 
        }
        public static void g() {
            System.out.println(&quot;Z.g()&quot;);
        }
    }
    
    @Retention(RetentionPolicy.RUNTIME)
    @interface Marker1 {}
    
    @Retention(RetentionPolicy.RUNTIME)
    @interface Marker2 {}

&lt;!-- language: lang-none --&gt;

    Marker1
    Z.g()
    Marker2
    Z.g()

